<div class="why-page">

  <p class="why-eyebrow">SINISTER STASH</p>

  <h1 class="why-title">Not What You Expected</h1>

  <div class="why-divider"></div>

  <div class="why-section">
    <p>In a better world, this page wouldn't need to exist.</p>
    <p>Not because people don't deserve the right to protect themselves--but because they wouldn't have to.</p>
    <p>We believe in that kind of world. One where people are supported before they're pushed to the edge. Where communities are resourced. Where mental health care is accessible, housing is stable, families are supported, and no one is left feeling so invisible or desperate that violence becomes an option.</p>
    <p>We want that world. And we support the policies that move us toward it--universal background checks, safe storage, red flag laws, and real investment in the conditions that actually prevent harm.</p>
    <p>But we don't live in that world.</p>
    <p>We live in one where queer people are being targeted. Right now.</p>
    <p>Where hate is loud, organized, and increasingly emboldened.</p>
    <p>Where safety isn't guaranteed--and for many of us, never has been.</p>
    <p>And in that reality, asking marginalized people to remain defenseless isn't something we can stand behind.</p>
    <p>This isn't about fear.</p>
    <p>This is about agency.</p>
    <p>This is about harm reduction.</p>
    <p class="why-emphasis">This is about survival--while we keep fighting for something better.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="why-section">
    <h2 class="why-heading">Who This Is For</h2>
    <p>Hate crimes against LGBTQ+ people have risen sharply over the past decade. Trans women of color, in particular, face some of the highest rates of lethal violence in the United States.</p>
    <p>For queer folks in rural areas, safety can be even more fragile--hours from community, limited access to support, and slower emergency response times. Being visible can come with real risk.</p>
    <p>These aren't hypotheticals. These are our people.</p>
    <p class="why-emphasis">And they deserve the right to make informed decisions about their own safety. Full stop.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="why-section">
    <h2 class="why-heading">This Isn't New</h2>
    <p>Self-defense in marginalized communities has always existed--whether it was recognized or not.</p>
    <p>Harriet Tubman carried a firearm to protect herself and the people she guided to freedom. She never lost a passenger.</p>
    <p>The Deacons for Defense and Justice armed themselves in the 1960s to protect civil rights workers when law enforcement wouldn't.</p>
    <p>The Black Panther Party began with community self-defense and cop-watching--far from the caricature many were taught.</p>
    <p>Groups like the Pink Pistols formed in response to violence against queer people, creating spaces where safety and identity could coexist.</p>
    <p>This isn't new. It's just often erased.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="why-section">
    <h2 class="why-heading">What We're Not</h2>
    <p>We are not the National Rifle Association.</p>
    <p>We don't share their politics, their priorities, or their vision of gun culture.</p>
    <p>We're not here for intimidation, posturing, or "tacticool" aesthetics.</p>
    <p>We're not here to convince anyone to arm themselves. That choice is deeply personal, and choosing <em>not</em> to is just as valid.</p>
    <p>And we're not in opposition to gun safety efforts. We want those protections too. We just believe people deserve autonomy over their safety while that work continues.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="why-section">
    <h2 class="why-heading">What We Are</h2>
    <p>We are the people who walked into gun culture and realized it wasn't built for us.</p>
    <p>So we built something else.</p>
    <p>Sinister Stash exists for queer people, women, BIPOC folks, leftists, progressives, and first-time gun owners who refuse to disappear just because a space wasn't designed with them in mind.</p>
    <p>We make things for people who carry--and don't fit the mold.</p>
    <p>Because representation matters.</p>
    <p>Because culture shifts when new people show up and refuse to shrink.</p>
    <p>Because every patch, every sticker, every quiet act of visibility changes what this space looks like--piece by piece.</p>
    <p class="why-emphasis">That's the long game. And we're playing it.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="why-divider"></div>

  <div class="why-section why-resources">
    <p>If you're exploring this for yourself, our resources page has some great places to start.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="why-closing">
    <p>We didn't want to need any of this.</p>
    <p>But we're not going to pretend we don't.</p>
    <p class="why-sig">-- Sinister Stash</p>
  </div>

</div>

